  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Imperial Edict Appointing the Lord of Siheung as Duke of Huai'an
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: '...Thus it is said. Our kingdom has established three ranks of nobility for our royal kinsmen—Duke, Marquis, and Earl—following the ancient ways of the Shang dynasty. You, a brilliant scion of our royal house, have long held the rank of Earl, these many years now. By virtue of your character and standing, you might well have ascended to Duke or Marquis long ago, yet circumstances delayed what should have come to pass. Now the barbarians press upon us with grave menace. Considering that our strength cannot contain them, we find ourselves compelled to seek peace and harmony with them, to ease their hostility. Should we pursue this course, none but our most illustrious kinsmen and worthy clans can serve as envoys. Among all our royal relatives, none possesses your refined qualities to shine before foreign courts, nor your commanding presence to subdue and bend the wild customs of their peoples. Thus we entrust this mission to you. Let your station be elevated and your authority strengthened, that your journey may be crowned with honor. We therefore grant you the rank of Duke, surpassing your former station, befitting your virtue and renown. Go forth and succeed in this task. Bring peace to our troubled realm, that we may not dishonor the sacred mandate passed down by our glorious ancestors. Is this not fitting? ...Thus it is said.'
  footnotes:
    - This edict promotes the Lord of Siheung from the rank of Earl (伯爵) to Duke (公爵), elevating him as an emissary to foreign powers during a period of military pressure.
    - The reference to 'the sacred mandate of our glorious ancestors' invokes the Confucian concept of the Mandate of Heaven, suggesting continuity with virtuous rulership of old.
